============================
Your app already uses RTDB. Shifting to a DB-triggered architecture means clients write/delete data directly to the database, and Cloud Functions react to those changes via functions.database.ref(...).onCreate/onUpdate/onDelete. Here's how each function maps:
HTTP Function	DB Trigger Replacement
cfCreatePost	Client writes to a pendingPosts/{pushId} node → onCreate trigger validates, sets authorId/publishedOn, moves to blogPosts/{pushId}
cfUpdatePost	Client writes to blogPosts/{postId} → onUpdate trigger validates the change
cfDeletePost	Client writes to deleteRequests/{postId} → onCreate trigger performs the actual delete
cfUpVote	Client writes to voteRequests/{postId}/{uid} → onCreate trigger validates + atomically increments blogPosts/{postId}/votes
cfGetPosts / cfGetPost	Eliminated — client reads directly from blogPosts/ via Firebase SDK using orderByChild/limitToFirst and security rules
Key changes required:
1. 
Replace HTTP handlers with functions.database.ref(...).onCreate/onUpdate/onDelete
2. 
Add a pendingPosts or staging path in the DB for creates/deletes so triggers can validate before committing
3. 
Use Firebase Security Rules on the staging paths to enforce auth (instead of manual token verification in cfCreatePost)
4. 
For reads — remove the HTTP functions entirely and have the client query RTDB directly (which is more scalable and cheaper)
For example, the create flow becomes:
export const onCreatePost = functions.database
  .ref("/pendingPosts/{postId}")
  .onCreate(async (snap, context) => {
    const data = snap.val();
    // validate, enrich with auth info
    data.publishedOn = Date.now();
    data.authorId = context.auth!.uid; // if using Firebase Auth
    data.views = 0;
    data.votes = 0;
    data.id = context.params.postId;
    // move to blogPosts
    await snap.ref.root.child("blogPosts").child(context.params.postId).set(data);
    await snap.ref.remove(); // clean up pending
  });